      <bioghist id="aspace_c03845e9e6b3ea2be0f44707e8d0da2a">
         <head>Ingrid Lothigius-Walder</head>
         <p>Ingrid Lothigius-Walder (1920-1998) was a Swedish-born actress and poet who emigrated to the United States in 1961. She settled in New York in 1965 and began to study photography. Her passion for street photography and portraits flourished. By 1980, her work was on exhibit at several galleries throughout New York.</p>
         <p>The history of the Harlem Jazz Festival is two-fold, beginning with the Harlem Cultural Festival of 1969 and the first Harlem Jazz Festival of 1978. The festival was a cornerstone of music concerts and exhibits celebrating Black American culture and music. Throughout the years, musicians such as Stevie Wonder, B. B. King, and Gladys Knight and the Pips performed.</p>
         <p>In 1981, Lothigius-Walder attended the Harlem Jazz Festival, and by invoking her unique style, captured images of the crowd as opposed to the performing artists. In so doing, she captured a glimpse of 1980s black street style in her photographs.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_7310b7aa2df7678f682d55c695039081">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Ingrid Lothigius-Walder collection of the Harlem Jazz Festival. James Weldon Johnson Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_ec24ab588c4c612f8e149871a40ace83">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Ingrid Lothigius-Walder collection of the Harlem Jazz Festival contains black and white photographs, contact sheets, and negatives related to the 1981 Harlem Jazz Festival. Additional printed material includes flyers relating to the photographer and other productions.</p>
      </scopecontent>
